    <!--
    This creates an expandable tree node labelled Appearance in the Edit tab.
    It is purely cosmetic; the order or structure of categories doesn't impact anything,
    and they are not associated to anything else using keys or whatnot.
    -->
    <category>
      <label>Appearance</label>
      <!--
      This creates a field labelled Name.
      Name is a special parameter, because in the .sav file it is a huge array
      of 25 character values, encoded as decimal numbers, but we just want to display
      it as a simple string.
      The <name></name> element tells PawnManager to display this as a "name" field,
      which determines how it interprets the data when reading from the .sav file,
      and what control to use in the UI (in this case, a simple text box).
      It's empty because there isn't anything more to say about this being a name field,
      unlike a drop-down where you need to specify what the options are, or a slider,
      where you need to give the range of values.
      -->
      <parameter>
        <key>name</key>
        <label>Name</label>
        <name></name>
      </parameter>
      <parameter>
        <key>gender</key>
        <label>Gender</label>
        <!--
        This is a drop-down field, which is important because most of the crowd-sourced research
        will involve these.
        First, you'll notice <disableCustom />.  That's a kind of rare option for drop-downs.
        If you don't specify it, a "Custom" option is automatically added to the drop-down,
        and the user is allowed to put in any value they want in the number field beside the drop-down.
        That is very important for research, because it lets you see what the current value in the .sav file is,
        or lets you put in your own value for testing (careful! that can crash your game!),
        before we have created a labelled option for that value.
        However, for something like Gender, we obviously know that the only two options are Male and Female,
        so there's no point in allowing the user to enter a custom value, as it will probably just crash their game.
        -->
        <dropDown>
          <disableCustom />
          <!--
          This is an option.  It contains the label for the option (purely cosmetic, it's not a key or anything),
          and the value used by the game for that option.
          So for gender, there are two possible values used by the game: 0 and 1,
          corresponding to male and female respectively.
          Again, the label is just for ease of use; we could call it "Boy" and "Girl", or "Man" and "Woman".
          -->
          <option>
            <label>Male</label>
            <value>0</value>
          </option>
          <option>
            <label>Female</label>
            <value>1</value>
          </option>
        </dropDown>
      </parameter>
      <parameter>
        <key>voice</key>
        <label>Voice</label>
        <!--
        This is a slider element, which allows the user to choose any number between a range of values.
        These aren't very nice, because nobody knows what "Voice = 8" means.
        Want to do something easy to help out?
        Change this to a drop-down, with descriptions for each voice!
        The "min" and "max" fields represent the minimum/maximum values that can be used *IN THE .SAV FILE*,
        and this is where the converter comes in.
        The converter converts the value for it to be displayed in the UI, both as the slider value and as the
        number in the text box beside the slider.
        The "plusOne" converter just adds one to the value, because the .sav file uses 0-based numbers,
        but the user likes to see 1-based (and they are labelled as 1-based in the character creator).
        -->
        <slider>
          <converter>plusOne</converter>
          <min>0</min>
          <max>11</max>
        </slider>
