  <!--
  This section tells PawnManager how to read a .sav file.
  More specifically, this section mirrors the structure of the .sav file,
  and tells PawnManager which elements to associate with a given key,
  used by the edit section.
  
  It basically works by reading an element in the config, gets the name of that element,
  then traverses the .sav file breadth-wise (i.e. without recursing into children)
  until it finds an element with that name.  If the element is a class (i.e. contains other elements),
  it recurses into that element, and if it's something else ("data" or "array" in the config),
  it grabs the key, looks up the key in the edit config, then reads or writes that data to/from the Pawn.
  
  So yes, this *mirrors* the structure of the .sav file.  It is very important that everything here
  is in exactly the same order as the .sav file, or else PawnManager will crash or give up or
  skip a section or something when it encounters an element out-of-order.
  
  The .sav file contains a nice array of three big structures, all with exactly the same elements,
  each containing the data of the three pawns.
  Pawns 1 and 2 just use their respective entries from that array (2 and 3), and cause no fuss.
  The Main Pawn is a little bitch though, and while it WRITES to entry 1 when you save the game,
  it READS its data from all over the goddamned place.
  For example, it reads its appearance from mSystemData/mEditPawn.  That means you need different
  behaviour depending on what Pawn you're exporting.
  Technically we don't have to write to that first entry when exporting the main Pawn,
  but we do anyway, just to mirror the behaviour of the game.
  As of release 0.1.0, I have no idea where the main Pawn reads its skills, vocation, level, etc. from,
  so you won't be able to export any of that to the main Pawn.
  -->
